                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 122.&#8212;<name
                                                type="person" key="669">Private Aaron T.
                                        Ward</name>, <name type="organization" key="676">Co. B, 20th
                                                Me.</name>; age 25; was admitted <date type="admit"
                                                when="1862-10-29">Oct. 29, 1862</date>, with
                                        diarrh&#339;a following typhoid fever. He was feeble and
                                        emaciated; the stools were generally natural in color, but
                                        liquid and occasionally streaked with blood.  On <date type="injury" when="1862-11-11">November 11</date>,
                                        the diarrh&#339;a still continuing, he was attacked with
                                        diphtheria characterized by suffocative paroxysms; he died
                                                <date type="death" when="1862-11-12">next
                                        day</date>.  <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination
                                        <date type="autopsy" when="1862-11-13">eighteen hours after death</date>: The larynx was
                                        &#339;dematous and lined with pseudo-membrane. The lungs
                                        were congested. The heart was normal, its right ventricle
                                        filled with a large firm clot. The stomach, liver and
                                        kidneys were normal. The glands of Br&#252;nner were enlarged;
                                        Peyer's glands thickened and in the lower portion of the
                                        ileum ulcerated.&#8212;<hi rend="italic"><name
                                                  type="hospital" key="189">Third Division
                                                  Hospital</name>, Alexandria, Va.</hi></p>                        
